<br>
Ok this is classic - you clearly dont understand what equal protection under the law actually means (as enshrined by the constitution and our laws. What this means is not 'Each case must decided on its' own merit. (and the rest of the paragraph of the above section)'. Equal protection under the law means that people have the right to expect to be equally protected by the law and 'from' the law. This means that if you commit murder - you will be arrested and charged in a timely fasion, and given resonably similair cases, you should expect a reasonably similar result. This does not happen. If you commit a serious crime in the US and you are wealthy and connected you are somewhat less likely to be charged than a poor person, and typically you have a much much higher chance of being convicted if you are poor. This is FACT.<br>
<br>
&lt;We have examples here in the States of justice being &quot;equally&quot; applied. It's such lovely things as mandatory sentencing for drug offenses and the Three Strikes program. I am not a Liberal guy, but even I can see that a first time offender with a pocket full of LSD does not merit 20 years in jail. The state of California does, though.&gt;<br>
