Right, I don’t understand what Equal Protection means? Equal Protection statutes allow for the same basic protection under the law for each person regardless of standing. These protections are, for example, from unreasonable search and seizure, double jeopardy, cruel and unusual punishment, et al. A wealthy man is read his Miranda Rights same as a poor man. A wealthy man enjoys the benefits of the 5th Amendment much as a poor man. All have the same basic protection under the law. How do you not see this?<br>
<br>
You seem to have a problem with the outcome of the trial. And? The outcome of the trial is not part of the package. Equal Protection works to keep you safe from, multiple trials, unfair evidence practices, etc. Regardless of the outcome of a trial, each person enjoys those basic protections.  Those protections don’t guarantee an outcome though. If you have a problem with what these high power types do in courtrooms, remember that a jury of our peers handed down the final decision in most of these cases. Thus it is our fault.<br>
