Single language? Did I say a single language? Why, no. I said a “common language”. The United States of America does not have a single language, but we do have a predominant “common language” in American. In EU offices, their EU code mandates that there will be at least one person available that is conversant in any language of any EU member you might choose to ask for. Should Slobodia (a name made up on the spot so as to not be insensitive and labeling towards small individual sub-entities within the EU) be a member of the EU and officially speak Slobodian, it matters little if there are only 500 people in the whole country. EU offices will have to have a Slobodian-conversant person available to each office. This is a logistics nightmare waiting to happen, but more to the point, it enforces lingual separatism instead of encouraging integration via an attempt to decide on a common tongue. <br>
<br>
A common tongue will not happen though, as the individual sub-entities (I still love that phrase) are very nationalistic and proud of their own languages. France actually has a ministry in its’ government dedicated to the preservation of the French language. They actively make up new terms for foreign slang that might invade France. Germany has a similar body. You claim to speak German, you should thereby know what they call such things as astronauts (cloud walkers or some-such, IIRC from what my limited knowledge of Deutsche produces). A ministry devoted to the preservation of one’s distinct nationalist language is fairly contrary to the aims of integration.<br>
