<br>
I remember a long time ago when it was referred to as the EEC, or European Economic Community. This wasn’t an official name, just a proposed one. Near as I can tell, it’s a much more accurate one thoughl. The individual sub-entities (/snicker) of the EU have changed little, excepting the aspect of currency and such currency related issues as taxation. Common defense, for instance, has not been an issue for quite some time as most EU members were members, in good standing, of NATO or, alternatively, the Warsaw Pact. Now that WP has fallen, most of the previous WP members became NATO members. Heck, even Russia has a pseudo membership-in NATO.  As to the EU Parliament, I am waiting for the first decision that puts the EUP at odds with the sitting govt of a member nation. This will be the big litmus test. Will the EU stand or fall? Odds are that the first time this happens, it will be with some piddly little Slobodia-type individual sub-entity (LOL) that the world press will care little about. I doubt they’ll have the cojones to stand up to Germany, France, England, etc.<br>
<br>
Still, the point I am making is that the EU is primarily an economic concern. It provides financial services mostly. Common currency, taxations, arbitration (hey, there’s that word again) between members, and other such commerce-assistive tasks. It sounds more and more like NAFTA to me, though a bit more far reaching in the common currency bit. Still, Argentina uses US Dollars now, could Mexico be so far behind?<br>
