&lt;snip link to speech&gt;<br>
<br>
Right, the speech talks about the need to transform from a Confederacy to a Federation, did you catch the implicit meaning behind that? The EU is a Confederation, period. Do you understand what a Confederation is? How about a Federation? Do you understand that we have a Federal government whereas they has a confederation of nations? Can you comprehend the difference?<br>
<br>
Some nice quotes from the speech, in an area where the speaker is discussing problems facing the EU, &quot;[sic] the problems and challenges facing Europe have wound themselves into a knot that will be very hard to undo in the current framework:&quot; &lt;snip whinges about currency problems, EU Commision scandals, and overly aggressive expansion&gt; &quot;the poor acceptance of the EU Parliament and low turn-outs for European elections&quot;. Man, sounds like he is saying that the European people just aren't all fired up and rowdy about the EU. Can't blame em. I'd be pretty ticked off if someone told me that I was no longer an American and was not a Western Hemispheric Unionist along with our Canadian, Mexican, and South American sub-entity friends.<br>
<br>
Other areas talk about how the EU Parliament needs to have real power to survive. Wait! Could that mean that, much like I've said previously, the EU Parliament is not the powerhouse you make it out to be?<br>
<br>
Another quote from the speech (and thanks for providing me with so much good support for my argument): &quot;Of course this simple solution (Roy Note: total Federation of EU) is immediately criticized as being unworkable. Europe is not a new continent (Roy note: Didn't I say this?), so the criticism goes, but full of different peoples, cultures, languages and histories (Roy note: I'm pretty sure that I said that) The nation-states are realities that simply cannot be erased, and more globalization and Europeanization create superstructures and anonymous actors remote from the citizens, the more people will cling to the nation-states that give them comfort and security,&quot;. The speaker then imeediately follows this with, &quot;Now I sahre these objections, because they are correct.&quot;<br>
<br>
Damn, your own source agrees more with what I've said so far than with you. Unlike you though, the speaker does advance some alternatives to the problems at hand. This is a good thing. Still, everything that the speech identified as a currently existing problem was present in my litany of concerns about the EU. You sought to refute what I was saying as incorrect, and then one of your own sources shows the EU to be as ineffectual and strife-ridden as I hypothesized it would be.<br>
<br>
The irony, again, is beautiful.<br>
<br>
Perhaps this may convince you that simply providing a source sans good explanation is a bad idea, and not equivalent to offering supports for your points. Then again, perhaps I am naive to hope that you will learn anything.<br>
<br>
